Meal plan + meal prep PART 1! 🍋

As a personal chef who also plans and preps for 4 other families every week, being organized with my meals is the only way to maintain healthy eating, good energy, and amazing digestion for myself and my family. 

I know you’re overwhelmed with doing this in your home. With a never ending to do list, it’s another thing that’s filling your mental load. I’m here to help. 

👉🏼 These are my 4 tips to make your weekly meal planning + prep a little bit easier:

1) Figure out what your week looks like: How many meals do you actually need? Are you getting takeout one night or doing lunch with a co worker or have a birthday party to attend? This matters when you plan. 

2) Pick your meals + snacks: Let me tell you a secret. You’re not going to make a recipe with 267 ingredients on a Wednesday night when you’re scrambling to get dinner on the table. Just pick easy meals with minimal ingredients. Don’t overcomplicate it. 

3) Choose your meal days and what you’re going to prep ahead vs make the day/night of. Your game plan is key here! The more you plan now the less you have to worry about later. 

4) Organize your grocery list: Section it off like you’re shopping in the store. Makes it so much easier and efficient. 

This can all be simple. But I know each step in itself can be a lot to think about if you’re just getting started. So I have your solution 👇🏼

In my online course, the Prep Like A Personal Chef Academy, I break these steps down even further in a 4 part video series to take the overwhelm out of feeding yourself and your family for good. Plus you get this cool meal planning template and tons more for $47. Link in bio to finally stop asking, “what’s for dinner?”

Stay tuned for part 2! 👩🏼‍🍳

Some meal prep is better than no meal prep 💁🏼‍♀️

The best thing about meal prepping is that you can make it anything you want it to be. There’s more than one way to meal prep so you have to find what works best for YOU and your family.

But if I can offer advice as a mom, personal chef, business owner, and sole caretaker of the meals in my home, it’s this 👇🏼

🍋Pick your pain points and start there🍋

👉🏼If you find yourself skipping lunch or getting takeout a lot, prep lunches.

👉🏼If you get to dinner time and there’s no way you’re chopping veggies, prep those
ingredients. 

👉🏼If mornings are wild and you know you aren’t getting a nutritious breakfast everyday, prep smoothies. 

You don’t have to do a full week of meal prep for it to help you. Although, that is a dream during the week to not cook! 

🌟Your takeaway is this: do what you can easily incorporate now, what you need the most first, then build from there 🌟

If you’re ready to have meal prep in your life but you’re overwhelmed on where to get started, I have your solution 👍🏼

I created an online course just for you. The Prep Like A Personal Chef Academy is a video course that teaches you my signature method to make meal planning and meal prep work FOR you. It can be simple. You just need to start. Link in bio to grab the course for only $47 👏🏼

The coziest chicken noodle soup 🥘

If you hate being cold like me, this soup warms you UP. It’s like a big, warm hug for your belly. 

And it’s super easy to make in the instant pot. Here’s the recipe 👇🏼

2 Tbsp olive oil 
1/2 yellow onion, chopped 
3 stalks celery, chopped 
4 carrots, peeled and sliced 
1” fresh ginger, minced
4 garlic cloves, minced 
2 boneless, skinless chicken breasts 
8 cups chicken broth 
1 1/2 cups noodle of choice (I recommend @traderjoes quinoa and brown rice spirals to make this gluten free)
1/2 cup cilantro, chopped 
3 lemons, juiced 
1 tsp salt
1 tsp Italian seasoning 
1/2 tsp black pepper
Crushed red pepper flakes (if you like it spicy) 

Turn your instant pot on sauté setting and add in your olive oil, onion, celery, carrots, ginger, garlic, and half of the spices. Sauté until veggies begin to soften, about 5 minutes. Add in your chicken breasts, chicken broth, and remaining spices. Close the lid on your instant pot and set to high pressure for 10 minutes. 
Release the steam immediately when done, remove the chicken breasts and set aside. 
Turn the instant pot back on sauté setting until the soup comes to a boil, add in your noodles and cook. While your noodles are cooking, shred your chicken. When the noodles are done, add your chicken back in along with your cilantro and lemon juice. Add crushed red pepper if desired. Now you’re ready to eat and enjoy! 

🌟Save this post to make later!

What are you meal prepping today?

@traderjoes is the greatest for “low-effort helpers” as I like to call them. These 5 ingredients from Trader Joe’s come together in 15 minutes for a super delicious pasta. 

1 bag (16oz) Brown Rice + Quinoa Fusilli Gluten-Free Pasta 
2, 14.5oz containers Bruschetta Sauce 
2, 12oz containers marinated fresh mozzarella cheese balls, drained
1/2 cup basil, chopped 
2-4 Tbsp balsamic vinegar (add to your liking) 

Boil your noodles and strain. 
Add to a large bowl, then mix in the remaining ingredients. That’s it! This is great served warm or as a cold pasta salad for meal prep 👏🏼
